nonStandard.name: Non-Standard Units
nonStandard.notes: Units that don't fit into a specific system

hour.notes: 1/24 of day. The hour was developed by astrologers in Classical antiquity.

commonYear.notes: Common Year - 365 days of 86400 seconds. Maybe si.

minuta.notes: 1/60 of day. Used by ancient astrologers.

secunda.notes: 1/3600 of day. Used by ancient astrologers.

mileUSSurvey.notes: Used exclusively for land survey. Used to be statute mile

usSurveyFoot.notes: Used exclusively for land survey. Used to be statute foot

fathom.notes: The nautical use and definition of fathom varied widely

palmus.notes: palm width - 1/4 pes. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

palmusMajor.notes: palm length - 3/4 pes - in late period only. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

ell.notes: This is the English ell, lengths vary from 0.5m (cubit) to 1.372m

ellScotish.notes: This is the Scotish ell, lengths vary from 0.5m (cubit) to 1.372m

league.notes: Originally meant the distance a person could walk in an hour

astronomicalUnit.notes: Non-SI unit accepted for use with the SI, and whose value in SI units must be obtained experimentally

lightSecond.notes: Distance light travels in vacuum in 1 second

lightMinute.notes: Distance light travels in vacuum in 60 seconds

lightHour.notes: Distance light travels in vacuum in 3600 seconds

lightDay.notes: Distance light travels in vacuum in 24 light-hours, 86,400 light-seconds

lightWeek.notes: Distance light travels in vacuum in 7 light-days, 604,800 light-seconds

lightYear.notes: Distance light travels in vacuum in 365.25 days

atomicMassUnit.notes: Non-SI unit accepted for use with the SI, and whose value in SI units must be obtained experimentally

uncia.notes: Roman ounce. 1/12 libra. Based on 1 libra = 328.9 g

libra.notes: Roman pound. Based on 1 libra = 328.9 g

newton.notes: May have rounding error. Check values

delisle.notes: May have rounding error. Check values

radian.notes: Only metric prefixes of milli, micro, and nano are acceptable and not in pure math

litre.notes: A litre was originally the metric base unit for volume. Now non-SI metric.

ligula.notes: Liquid, Dry. 1/48 sextarius. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

cyathus.notes: Liquid, Dry. 1/12 sextarius. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

acetabulum.notes: Liquid, Dry. 1/8 sextarius. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

quartarius.notes: Liquid, Dry. 1/4 sextarius. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

hemina.notes: Liquid, Dry. 1/2 sextarius. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

sextarius.notes: Liquid, Dry. 1/6 congius. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

amphoraQuadrantal.notes: Liquid. 8 congii. One cubic pes. Standard amphora size. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

modius.notes: Dry. 16 sextarii. Alt: 8.62e-3. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

modiusCastrensis.notes: Dry. 24 sextarii. Alt: 12.93e-3. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

are.notes: Commonly only gas centi-, deci-, dec-, hect- prefixes. Not an si unit in it's own right.

hectare.notes: Technically and are with hect prefix but is only version of are accepted within broader si context.

squarePerche.notes: The french version of a square perch

pesQuadratus.notes: square foot - 1 pes^2. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

scrupulum.notes: the square of the standard 10-foot measuring rod. Jugerum division. 100 pedes^2 - 1/288 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

actusSimplex.notes: 4 x 120 pedes = 480 pedes^2. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

uncia.notes: Jugerum division. 2400 pedes^2 - 1/12 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

clima.notes: 60 x 60 pedes = 3600 pedes^2. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

actusQuadratus.notes: Jugerum division. 14400 pedes^2 - 1/2 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

centuria.notes: 200 jugerum. Was 100 jugera. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

dimidiumScrupulum.notes: Jugerum division. 50 pedes^2 - 1/576 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

duoScrupula.notes: Jugerum division. 200 pedes^2 - 1/144 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

sextula.notes: Jugerum division. 400 pedes^2 - 1/72 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

sicilicus.notes: Jugerum division. 600 pedes^2 - 1/48 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

semiuncia.notes: Jugerum division. 1200 pedes^2 - 1/24 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

sextans.notes: Jugerum division. 4800 pedes^2 - 1/6 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

quadrans.notes: Jugerum division. 7200 pedes^2 - 1/4 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

triens.notes: Jugerum division. 9600 pedes^2 - 1/3 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

quincunx.notes: Jugerum division. 12000 pedes^2 - 5/12 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

septunx.notes: Jugerum division. 16800 pedes^2 - 7/12 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

bes.notes: Jugerum division. 19200 pedes^2 - 2/3 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

dodrans.notes: Jugerum division. 21600 pedes^2 - 3/4 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

dextans.notes: Jugerum division. 24000 pedes^2 - 5/6 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

deunx.notes: Jugerum division. 26400 pedes^2 - 11/12 jugerum. Based on 1 pes = 0.296m

pascal.notes: Common prefixes: hecto-, kilo-, mega-, giga-

bar.notes: Accepted prefixes: mega-, kilo-, deci-, centi-, milli-

torr.notes: Only commonly used prefix is milli-

metrePerSecond.notes: This is of type customary NOT si because you can't actually apply prefixes to it

knotAdmiralty.notes: More research needed on systems and origins

machNumber.notes: Based on standard sea level conditions and at 15 °C. Additionally should be written Mach 2.3 (unit name first)

speedOfSound.notes: Based on standard sea level conditions and at 15 °C.

debye.notes: Still used within SI as all SI prefixes are too large for certain applications.

electricResistance.notes: Impedance (Z) and Reactance (X) have the same units as resistance and in this context are considered equivalent

ohm.notes: Naming quantities may be done in the form 5.6 Ω => 5R6 to avoid 'rubbing off' decimal place

megohm.notes: Replaces the standard SI prefix mega- for ohms

microhm.notes: Replaces the standard SI prefix micro- for ohms

gigohm.notes: Replaces the standard SI prefix giga- for ohms

centi.notes: Is rare for systems other than length
